# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
conversation: act5.the_ledger | Act V — The Ledger
node: 0 | Jergal
  *(If you walk the golden road: the Wall's entire ten-thousand-year ledger of the discarded lies open before you, every Faithless soul a single handwritten line. The scribe sets the pen in your hand.)* Here is the mercy I abandoned. Each line is a person. Each person is a story no one read before they were filed under nothing. You may judge them — truly judge them, one soul at a time, by hand — for as long as you are willing to stand here. It can take as long as you let it. Most would delegate it to a rule. *(quietly)* Will you read them?
  enter: SET act5.ledger_opened
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Jergal
  I will not pretend it is not tedious. Eternity made it tedious for me, and I am the patience that filed the first soul. But tedium is the texture of real mercy — anything faster is a rule, and a rule is how they got walled in the first place. *(The first name waits under your pen.)* Read as many as your heart can hold. Each one you read by hand is one the law will never again file under nothing. Begin where you like. They have all waited the same ten thousand years.
  * "I'll read every one. However long it takes." -> all | fx SET ending.ledger_read_all, SET deed.judged_by_hand
  * "I'll read until my heart can't hold another, and then I'll come back tomorrow, and the next day." -> some | fx SET ending.ledger_read_some
  * [INSIGHT 20] "You're not asking me to judge them. You're asking me to witness them. That's the mercy you abandoned — not the verdict, the attention." -> witness ?? verdict
  * "Help me build a kinder rule, so no one ever has to do this by hand again." -> rule
node: all | Jergal
  *(The first scribe of the dead watches you bend to the first name, and something in the ancient patience cracks — not from strain, but from relief.)* Every one. *(quietly)* Do you know, in ten thousand years, no one has offered to read every one. They always reach for the rule by the hundredth name. *(He does not leave your side.)* Then I will read them with you, crack. It is my abdication; let it be my penance. Name by name. Story by story. Until the Wall is not a wall but a *library* — every discarded soul, at last, *read.*
  enter: SET ending.ledger_read_all, SET deed.judged_by_hand, SET jergal.returns_to_the_work
  auto: closing
node: some | Jergal
