  enter: SET ending.ledger_read_some, SET deed.judged_by_hand
  auto: closing
node: witness | Jergal
  *(The ancient regard fixes on you with something almost like awe.)* ...The attention. Not the verdict. *(very quietly)* Ten thousand years, and you are the first to name what I actually abandoned. I told myself I gave up *judging* them. I gave up *seeing* them. The verdict was always easy — *Faithless*, next. It was the *looking* I could not sustain. *(He sets his hand beside yours on the ledger.)* Then witness them, crack. That is the whole of the mercy. To be the eyes that finally stay. Read on. I will learn to look again beside you.
  enter: SET ending.ledger_read_all, SET act5.mercy_is_attention, jergal.understands_at_last
  auto: closing
node: rule | Jergal
  *(The scribe considers this for a long, careful moment.)* A kinder rule. *(slowly)* Be wary, crack — a rule is exactly what walled them. But a rule *written by a hand that first read ten thousand of them, one at a time*... that might be a law instead of an abdication. *(He sets the pen more firmly in your grip.)* Then read enough to earn the rule. A hundred. A thousand. Until you know in your bones what you are legislating *for.* And then write a law that remembers it was once a person under a pen. That, I could not do. I never read enough to earn it.
  enter: SET ending.ledger_writes_new_law, SET deed.judged_by_hand, ending.golden_road_open
